body:
To observe this bug, run Verilator with `-fno-dfg` or `-fno-dfg-peephole`. Otherwise the DFG optimizations take care of this logic before the bit op tree optimizer.
Test case:
```systemverilog
module t(input [5:0] A);
    wire [6:0] B;
    assign B = {1'h0, A};
    wire C = ~(B[6]);
    wire D = (|A) | C;

    initial
        if (~D) $stop;
        else $finish;
endmodule
```
Generated code:
```cpp
if ((IData)((0U != (IData)(vlSelf->A)))) {
    VL_FINISH_MT("test.sv", 9, "");
} else {
    VL_STOP_MT("test.sv", 8, "");
}    
```
The `| C` part gets optimized out, even though `C == ~(B[6]) == ~(0) == 1`.
The problem is somwehere in `V3Const`'s `ConstBitOpTreeVisitor`. Running Verilator with `-fno-const-bit-op-tree` fixes the issue.
